# Deploying {{ name }}

All deploy and flag operations go through `.ymir/deploy.py`. Run it from the project root.

## After making code changes

Once tests pass, deploy to dev. **The deploy takes 3-5 minutes** (build + SSH).
Run it detached so it survives shell timeouts, then poll the log:

```bash
# Step 1 — start detached (run this as ONE command)
cd /workspace/{{ name }} && nohup python3 .ymir/deploy.py dev > /tmp/deploy.log 2>&1 & disown && echo "Deploy running, PID $!"

# Step 2 — wait ~30s, then check log (repeat until done)
sleep 30 && cat /tmp/deploy.log

# Step 3 — keep checking every 30s until you see ✓ or ✗
sleep 30 && cat /tmp/deploy.log
```

Success looks like: `✓ dev  http://...`
Failure looks like: `✗ deploy failed`

Do NOT use `tail -f` — it will be killed and take the deploy with it.

## Feature flag lifecycle

```bash
# See current state (flags, deploy status)
python3 .ymir/deploy.py status

# Create a new flag
python3 .ymir/deploy.py flag-add <flag> [optional description]

# Delete a flag (removes from feature_flags.yaml + state)
python3 .ymir/deploy.py flag-delete <flag>

# Turn a flag ON in dev (to test the feature)
python3 .ymir/deploy.py activate <flag>

# Turn a flag OFF in dev
python3 .ymir/deploy.py deactivate <flag>

# Dark-launch to prod (code ships, all flags stay OFF)
python3 .ymir/deploy.py prod

# Release to users (flag ON in prod, redeploys)
python3 .ymir/deploy.py release <flag>

# Rollback (flag OFF in prod, redeploys)
python3 .ymir/deploy.py rollback <flag>
```

## Full workflow for a new feature

1. `python3 .ymir/deploy.py flag-add my_feature "what it does"`
2. Write code gated behind the flag, write tests, make them pass
3. `python3 .ymir/deploy.py activate my_feature` → test on dev
4. `python3 .ymir/deploy.py prod` → dark launch (flag OFF in prod)
5. `python3 .ymir/deploy.py release my_feature` → ship to users
6. (if needed) `python3 .ymir/deploy.py rollback my_feature` → revert
7. (cleanup) `python3 .ymir/deploy.py flag-delete my_feature` after full adoption

## Rules

- Never run `docker` commands directly — Docker is on the remote server, not here.
- Never run `python3 ymir.py` — that tool lives outside this project.
- Never modify `Dockerfile` — it is managed by ymir, not by agents.
- Never use `sudo` — deploy.py handles permissions itself.
- Always deploy to dev and verify before deploying to prod.
- New features must go behind a feature flag (see `feature_flags.yaml`).
